data.name: query
data.description: Keywords to search. Lucene query syntax is supported, e.g., +title:Trump. Available field names are 'title', 'meta', 'content', 'canonical_url' and 'date_published'. The field date_published is saved as text 'yyyy-mm-ddThh:mm:ss', you can use termrangefilter on this field, e.g., the string 'pizzagate AND date_published:[2016-10-28 TO 2016-12-04]' will query documents with any fields contain pizzagate and the date_published is between 2016-10-28 to 2016-12-04.

data.name: sort_by
data.description: Choices {relevant, recent}. Specify how to sort the result, by the most relevant or recent. Default relevant.

data.name: use_lucene_syntax
data.description: Whether the query string is in Lucene query syntax. By default, it is false meaning all Lucene reserved characters would be removed.
Search indexed webpages and return article entities.

domains
data.description: Return articles restrained to these domains. Default is None, return all available articles. If 'fact_checking', return only fact checking articles. If 'claim', return only claim articles. If 'fake', return articles from sites marking as fake by our configuration. You can also input a domain list. The format is a JSON string representing a list of domain, e.g., ["snopes.com", "breitbart.com"] (should be double quotes). Note, here 'fake' is considered as a subset of 'claim' and `site_type` is always be 'fact_checking' or 'claim'.

data.name: past_hours
data.description: Integer value. The latest time range is defined as from `NOW-past_hours` to `NOW` (both inclusive). Our crawling of articles is not real time, you are suggested to start this number from 2.

ids
data.description: A list of article ids to query. Format [id1, id2, ...]

data.name: resolution
data.description: The resolution of timeline. 'H': hour, 'D': day, 'W': week, 'M': month. Default is 'D'.
Return timeline of tweets.
data.name: Timeline
most_recent
data.description: When set to true, return the most recent available top articles, if there is no top articles for the `upper_day`.

data.name: upper_day
data.description: When calculating the most sharing articles, we consider a 30 days window. The right bound controls the position of the window and it is called `upper_day`, e.g., if `upper_day='2016-12-01'`, then the window ranges between '2016-11-01' and '2016-12-01'. Input format is 'yyyy-mm-dd', and the default value is the date of yesterday. Note that the endpoint does not accept any input more recent than the date of yesterday. Also currently the minimal upper_day value is '2017-02-07'.
Return top 20 most sharing articles for the last 30 days.

data.name: upper_day
data.description: When calculating the most active users, we consider a 30 days window. The right bound controls the position of the window and it is called `upper_day`, e.g., if `upper_day='2016-12-01'`, then the window ranges between '2016-11-01' and '2016-12-01'. Input format is 'yyyy-mm-dd', and the default value is the date of yesterday. Note that the endpoint does not accept any input more recent than the date of yesterday. Also currently the minimal upper_day value is '2016-12-12'.
